context: <a0_0><b5_0>The William Allen White School of Journalism and Mass Communications<b5_0/><a0_0/> is recognized for its ability to prepare students to work in a variety of media when they graduate. The school offers two tracts of study: <a1_0><b6_0>News and Information and Strategic Communication<b6_0/><a1_0/>. This professional school teaches its students reporting for <a2_0><b7_0>print, online and broadcast<b7_0/><a2_0/>, strategic campaigning for PR and advertising, photojournalism and video reporting and editing. The J-School's students maintain various publications on campus, including The University Daily Kansan, <a3_0><b8_0>Jayplay magazine<b8_0/><a3_0/>, KUJH TV and KJHK radio. In 2008, the Fiske Guide to Colleges praised the KU J-School for its strength. In 2010, the School of Journalism and Mass Communications finished second at the prestigious <a4_0><b9_0>Hearst Foundation<b9_0/><a4_0/> national writing competition.
